    Statistics 195/CME 195</br>
    Spring 2017</br>
    Haben Michael</br>
    <p class="c2 c8"><span></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c4">[from
        bulletin] </span><span class="c1 c6">This short course runs for
        the first four weeks of the quarter and is offered in fall and
        spring. It is recommended for students who want to use R in
        statistics, science, or engineering courses and for students who
        want to learn the basics of R programming. The goal of the short
        course is to familiarize students with R&#39;s tools for
        scientific computing. Lectures will be interactive with a focus on
        learning by example, and assignments will be
        application-driven. No prior programming experience is
        assumed. </span>
      <span class="c1 c5"><a class="c3" href="intro.pdf">Intro slides</a></span><span class="c1 c6">.</span></p>
    <p class="c2 c8"><span class="c1
                                  c6"></span></p><p class="c2"><span class="c4
                                                                            c9">Requirements: </span><span class="c4">3 short (less than 3hrs)
        programming-based assignments, each receiving a grade of at least
        60%. Extra credit received on one assignment cannot be
                                  applied to another
                                  assignment. Attendance won't be
                                  taken, but students are responsible
                                  for both administrative and course material covered in class.</span></p><p class="c2 c8">

    <p><span>Please review the <a href="http://csmajor.stanford.edu/HonorCode.shtml">CS honor
          code</a>, which binds students enrolled in this course.</span></p>

    <p class="c2"><span class="c4 c9">Similar courses: </span><span class="c4">If you want a short intro to R from the ground up, you could try my </span><span class="c0"><a class="c3"
